## Choosing Your Weapon

### Understanding Weapon Categories

Different weapon categories suit different combat approaches:

**Heavy Weapons** deliver maximum damage through raw force. You sacrifice agility and flexibility for devastating strikes that end fights quickly. Every hit matters more, but you're less able to dodge or maneuver. Best for characters who can afford to trade mobility for power—armored fighters who don't need to dodge because they can simply absorb hits.

**Medium Weapons** balance damage with versatility. Most can use either Might or Grace, making them adaptable to different fighting styles. You can pair them with shields for defense or wield them two-handed for extra damage. These weapons suit characters who want options rather than specialization.

**Light Weapons** emphasize speed and precision over raw power. Lower base damage but no penalties, plus bonuses to Finesse actions. Perfect for characters who rely on Grace—rogues, duelists, and anyone who needs to pick a lock while holding a weapon. The reduced damage matters less when you're hitting weak points.

**Reach Weapons** let you attack from safer distances. You hit enemies from Close range—one zone away—keeping them from retaliating effectively. The same base damage as light weapons, but the positioning advantage often matters more than raw damage numbers. Excellent for tactical fighters who understand battlefield geometry.

**Thrown Weapons** provide flexible range options. Engage at melee or Close range depending on circumstances. You generate bonus Momentum when hitting at Close range, rewarding risky throws. Most thrown weapons return to your hand or are inexpensive enough to carry multiples.

**Ranged Weapons** excel at Far range where other weapons can't reach. Bows deal extra damage at maximum range, rewarding positioning. The penalty when Engaged makes these weapons vulnerable in melee—archers need allies to keep enemies away or tactics to maintain distance.

### Weapon Selection by Role

**If you're a frontline defender**, consider medium weapon with shield. The +2 Guard from a shield significantly improves survival, and medium weapons provide solid damage. Alternatively, heavy two-handed weapons make you threatening enough that enemies can't ignore you—sometimes the best defense is making yourself too dangerous to leave alone.

**If you're a damage dealer**, heavy weapons provide the highest base damage (2d6+2 versus 2d6). Combined with high Might and Aggressive stance, you become a threat enemies must address immediately. Some medium weapons offer critical hit bonuses that can match or exceed heavy weapon damage when you roll well.

**If you're a skirmisher**, light weapons or reach weapons suit hit-and-run tactics. Light weapons don't slow you down; reach weapons let you strike from safe distances. Thrown weapons give you flexibility to adapt range as tactical situations evolve.

**If you're an archer**, choose based on your expected engagement range. Longbows excel at Far range with +1 damage. Shortbows work at all ranges without specialization. Crossbows penetrate armor but reload slowly—one shot every other turn, so make it count.

### Damage Comparison

Understanding actual damage output helps you make informed choices:

**Base Damage by Category:**
- Heavy: 2d6+2 (average 9 damage)
- Medium: 2d6+1 (average 8 damage)
- Light/Reach/Thrown/Ranged: 2d6 (average 7 damage)

**With Attribute Modifiers:**
A character with +2 Might wielding a heavy weapon rolls 2d6+4 (weapon +2, attribute +2), averaging 11 damage per hit. That same character with a light weapon averages 9 damage—only 2 points less.

**With Stance Bonuses:**
Aggressive stance adds +1 damage. Our heavy weapon wielder now averages 12 damage, while the light weapon user averages 10. The gap narrows when you factor in that light weapons enable shield use (+2 Guard) or don't penalize Grace.

The insight: Damage differences are real but not overwhelming. Choose weapons for tactical benefits and character concept, not purely for damage optimization.

### Special Properties Explained

**Versatile** weapons can be wielded one-handed or two-handed. Use one hand normally, or grip with both hands for +1 damage. The longsword exemplifies this—1d6+1 one-handed, 2d6+2 two-handed. Switch freely as situations demand.

**Ignore DR** bypasses damage reduction. Maces and heavy crossbows penetrate armor that would stop other weapons. When facing heavily armored opponents, these weapons become significantly more effective than their base damage suggests.

**Critical Bonuses** add effects on critical hits. Greatswords cleave into adjacent enemies. Greataxes triple their attribute bonus. Battle axes grant bonus damage dice. These properties reward aggressive play and create dramatic moments.

**Loading** weapons fire every other turn. Crossbows trade rate of fire for other benefits—armor penetration, no attribute requirements, consistency. Plan your shots carefully when each one costs a full turn to reload.

**Concealment** makes weapons easy to hide. Daggers slip into boots or sleeves. This matters for social situations, infiltration, and anywhere weapons aren't openly carried.

